Answer.Ans1: Don Bradman turned 20 years old the year he made his international test debut. He was born on August 27, 1908, and made his test debut on November 30, 1928, against England. The reason for his young age at the time of his debut was his exceptional talent and skill in cricket, which allowed him to make an early entry into international cricket.
Answer.Ans2: Don Bradman turned 40 years old in the year he played his last international test match.
Answer.Ans3: The domestic team Don Bradman played for the year he turned 30 was South Australia
Answer.Res1: The reason Don Bradman made his international test debut at a young age of 20 was primarily due to his extraordinary cricketing abilities and outstanding performance in domestic cricket. Bradman had already established himself as a prolific run-scorer in the Australian domestic circuit, amassing impressive records and capturing attention with his exceptional batting skills. His outstanding statistics and consistent performances made him a standout candidate for the national team, leading to his selection at a relatively young age. The cricketing fraternity recognized his immense talent and potential, and he quickly proved himself as one of the greatest batsmen in the history of the sport.
Answer.Res2: The reason for his retirement at a relatively early age was primarily due to his desire to retire on a high note and his focus on other aspects of his life. After a highly successful career spanning nearly two decades, Bradman felt that he had achieved all that he desired in the game of cricket. Additionally, he had been battling with health issues, including a severe bout of illness during the 1948 tour of England, which further influenced his decision to retire. Bradman's retirement marked the end of an illustrious career, leaving behind a remarkable legacy in the sport.
Answer.Res3: The reason for his association with South Australia was his desire to continue playing cricket at the domestic level and represent the state. Bradman had previously played for New South Wales from 1927/28 to 1933/34 but made the switch to South Australia for the 1935/36 season. This move provided him with more opportunities to showcase his skills and contribute to the team's success. Bradman's presence in the South Australia team further bolstered their batting lineup and helped them achieve significant victories in domestic cricket.
